<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-224-052  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 224 052.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Federal Computer Week  March 5 1990 v4 n9 p1(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>GSA, DOD meeting called to end FTS 2000 impasse. (General ServicesAdministration, Department of Defense)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Rivenbark, Leigh.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Officials from the General Services Administration (GSA) and theDepartment of Defense (DOD) are meeting to discuss the military'suse of ATandamp;T's FTS 2000 telecommunications system.andP;  The mainproblem is the use of the Defense Commercial Communications Office(Decco) as what GSA views as another layer of bureaucracy in theprocurement process.andP;  GSA proposes a six-month trial of a processin which some parts of DOD would purchase FTS 2000 servicesdirectly from ATandamp;T while most would buy the services throughDecco.andP;  GSA has questions regarding the speed of Decco's processesand possible conflicts in policy and in communication to vendorsand military agencies about the procurement process.andP;  DOD saysthat the slow pace is because of GSA's lack of response to a draftmemorandum.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   American Telephone and Telegraph Co. (contracts).andO;Ticker:    T.andO;Product:   FTS 2000 (Telecommunication switching system) (contracts).andO;Topic:     United States. General Services AdministrationUnited States. Department of DefenseTelecommunicationsMilitaryGovernment Contracts.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>